#Text=It seems very clear that this is not about trademark infringement .
#Text=Trademark law serves to protect consumers from being confused as to the source or origin of goods .
#Text=This is n't a trademark infringement case .
#Text=It is an attempt to litigate a defamation case in a forum that might not pay deference to the First Amendment .
#Text=This is n't a trademark infringement case .
#Text=It is an attempt to litigate a defamation case in a forum that might not pay deference to the First Amendment .
#Text=— Marc Randazza

#Text=On September 29 , 2009 , you requested that Glenn Beck agree to stipulate to the application of the United States Constitution , and also especially to the First Amendment to the U.S. Constitution .
#Text=Can you explain your rationale for this request ?
#Text=Have you heard back from Beck 's attorneys about this request ?
#Text=Mr. Beck has publicly stated , many times over , that he is offended at the thought of international law trumping the U.S. constitution .
#Text=I presumed that he would not want that to happen in this case .
#Text=His attorneys have not responded to my request .
#Text=What are the next steps that will occur in the Beck v. Eiland-Hall case ?
#Text=I presume that the arbitration panel will decide this case in my client 's favor .
#Text=Do you think that Glenn Beck will bring legal actions related to the Eiland-Hall website in the United States ?
#Text=How do you think such legal action would fare , specifically with regard to claims of libel/defamation ?
#Text=I do n't think so , but I 've seen many frivolous , stupid , and ultimately disastrous defamation suits filed in my career .
#Text=If you look at page 2 of my request for stipulation letter , it will articulate our position on that perfectly .
#Text=An article in the UK news magazine The First Post commented that Beck 's argument that the domain name of the Eiland-Hall website is itself defamatory " looks like a first in cyber law " .
#Text=Would you agree with this assessment ?
#Text=Have there been other similar cases with regard to this issue in cyber law ?
#Text=It is the first time that anyone has claimed that a mere domain name is defamatory .
#Text=— Marc Randazza
#Text=It really is not all that novel of an issue .
#Text=It is the first time that anyone has claimed that a mere domain name is defamatory , but big corporations have filed many wipo actions to try and get rid of " sucks " sites .
#Text=So , while the exact facts are a new one to me , there are well worn grooves in the road that govern the legal concepts in this case .
#Text=Are there any other points regarding the Beck v. Eiland-Hall case that you would like to elaborate or explain ?
